1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:17,596
Well, it takes three days really to get into the practice, sometimes four days.

2
00:00:18,658 --> 00:00:20,300
And then after that really it's up to you.

3
00:00:22,923 --> 00:00:28,452
But in a sense the minimum would be to get a good, the minimum would be seven days.

4
00:00:29,646 --> 00:00:31,248
But after that, the world's your oyster.

5
00:00:31,748 --> 00:00:32,329
Just go for it.

6
00:00:32,350 --> 00:00:32,770
Keep going.

7
00:00:33,350 --> 00:00:33,850
No stop.

8
00:00:35,813 --> 00:00:39,277
The classic time in the Mahasi tradition is three months.

9
00:00:40,618 --> 00:00:43,000
He said, if nothing happens in ten weeks, nothing will.

10
00:00:44,463 --> 00:00:45,203
You need a break.

11
00:00:48,066 --> 00:00:49,106
Yeah, that's it really.

12
00:00:49,127 --> 00:00:53,451
You need a break.

13
00:00:53,472 --> 00:00:56,115
And the things that you would do, would it be similar the days to what we did here?

14
00:00:56,134 --> 00:00:58,337
Yeah, well, in an ordinary...

15
00:00:58,722 --> 00:01:04,170
on an ordinary long retreat your meditation period will be an hour, an hour sitting, an hour walking, an hour sitting.

16
00:01:04,189 --> 00:01:09,777
Because I've heard that some Vipassanas where they're nearly sitting nearly all the time.

17
00:01:09,798 --> 00:01:10,018
Yeah.

18
00:01:10,097 --> 00:01:11,859
Has this been different?

19
00:01:11,879 --> 00:01:13,462
Has this been punctuated by a lot of walking?

20
00:01:14,243 --> 00:01:23,576
Yeah, no, we, in the, in some tradition, well in what, I think the tradition you're talking about is the taught by Goenka, the Ubakken tradition.

21
00:01:25,239 --> 00:01:28,003
That, that tradition, it's sort of, um,

22
00:01:28,625 --> 00:01:34,412
the actual practice combines a Samatha element, a calming element, with the Vipassana.

23
00:01:34,974 --> 00:01:37,358
So it's quite easy to sit with it for long times.

24
00:01:38,780 --> 00:01:43,966
And, yeah, it's up to the individual just to keep going, you see.

25
00:01:44,748 --> 00:01:49,555
The Mahasi Sayadaw taught a system which was pure Vipassana.

26
00:01:50,856 --> 00:01:52,340
And there's one or two others like that.

27
00:01:52,700 --> 00:01:58,108
Pure Vipassana, like there's no joy in it unless it comes up naturally.

28
00:01:58,882 --> 00:02:00,963
So it tends to be a little bit harder.

29
00:02:01,164 --> 00:02:04,647
The purification is much more intense.

30
00:02:05,847 --> 00:02:14,536
So, normally speaking, you'd have two or three days horror, and then a day of peace and happiness, and then the next lot will come up.

31
00:02:15,477 --> 00:02:17,479
It really is quite tough.

32
00:02:17,538 --> 00:02:21,562
You've been through it.

33
00:02:22,902 --> 00:02:26,066
Always, yeah.

34
00:02:26,086 --> 00:02:27,187
In silence.

35
00:02:27,508 --> 00:02:28,027
In silence.

36
00:02:28,699 --> 00:02:35,768
You would normally do, if you were doing a full Mahasi, you know, you would be walking and sitting 18 hours a day.

37
00:02:36,868 --> 00:02:39,592
Two hours for eating and rest and four hours sleep.

38
00:02:40,513 --> 00:02:42,455
That's the real program.

39
00:02:43,396 --> 00:02:44,677
You can do that at Satipanya.

40
00:02:47,441 --> 00:02:48,442
But that's not necessary.

41
00:02:48,461 --> 00:02:53,929
Six hours sleep, you can still become fully liberated with six hours sleep.

42
00:02:53,949 --> 00:02:55,229
But...

43
00:02:55,852 --> 00:03:25,842
but it's it's depends on the individual depends on remember that all you're doing all day is calming everything you're not indulging emotional states so there's not that energy being used up although you might do some exercise just to keep the body fit generally speaking you're very calm very steady you see

44
00:03:26,259 --> 00:03:28,842
So, of course, you find you do need less sleep.

45
00:03:30,685 --> 00:03:31,887
Yeah, you need much less sleep.

46
00:03:33,307 --> 00:03:46,022
Now, it doesn't mean to say that when you re-enter into daily life that you don't have to go back to a sleeping pattern because of just the pressures, just the energy you need to live in the society.

47
00:03:48,185 --> 00:03:50,427
Any of the persons do any component for fasting?

48
00:03:52,348 --> 00:03:56,534
Well, it's inbuilt because afternoon you don't eat, you see.

49
00:04:00,320 --> 00:04:08,733
Fasting itself in Buddhist understanding wouldn't be, they don't like you doing fast, not in the monastic world.

50
00:04:10,695 --> 00:04:19,267
They don't mind you, I mean, as far as they're concerned, the only reason for fasting would be a process of renunciation.

51
00:04:19,923 --> 00:04:21,504
You might do it for health reasons, of course.

52
00:04:21,545 --> 00:04:22,807
That's another thing altogether.

53
00:04:23,447 --> 00:04:30,456
But in terms of a spiritual practice, the only reason you lay off something is to see your attachment to it.

54
00:04:33,442 --> 00:04:35,543
I think I mentioned it now, sitting in front of the TV.

55
00:04:35,964 --> 00:04:39,389
That's a killer, that.

56
00:04:40,630 --> 00:04:42,413
And then you see what your relationship is, you see.

57
00:04:43,334 --> 00:04:44,536
So that's what you would do it for.

58
00:04:44,576 --> 00:04:47,600
Renunciation is one of the...

59
00:04:48,391 --> 00:04:50,173
one of the great spiritual practices.

60
00:04:51,634 --> 00:04:57,983
But you do it in order to see your attachment, and you have to sit with that renunciation until the attachment dies away.

61
00:04:58,023 --> 00:05:03,889
And then, so long as it's a wholesome activity, you can go back to doing it.

62
00:05:03,990 --> 00:05:14,161
But you always have to be slightly aware of how you're relating to it again, in terms of compulsive behavior, any psychological need.

63
00:05:15,357 --> 00:05:16,718
So what would you do with alcoholics?

64
00:05:16,738 --> 00:05:23,125
Would you put a bottle of wine in front of them?

65
00:05:23,146 --> 00:05:27,612
You don't want to tempt people too much.

66
00:05:27,632 --> 00:05:33,139
In giving up your attachments, I guess I would extend to something like a parent or a child.

67
00:05:33,939 --> 00:05:35,841
Yeah, it's always a very difficult one.

68
00:05:36,742 --> 00:05:42,629
The thing is, so long as there's a sense of self, by which we mean, I think I am

69
00:05:43,100 --> 00:06:10,778
this form this human being right so long as there's that feeling in us there'll always be attachment there's no way all we all we can do is be aware of how the attachment manifests and the attachment manifests always by way of holding on to yeah or pushing away or running away those are your basic manifestations so a parent say with a child

70
00:06:13,642 --> 00:06:19,608
When the child doesn't do what the parent wants the child to do, the parent gets angry, right?

71
00:06:20,069 --> 00:06:33,622
Now the anger is a manifestation of attachment, of having a desire to control the child, see?

72
00:06:34,322 --> 00:06:39,567
Now that doesn't mean to say that the child doesn't do what the parent wants it to do, right?

73
00:06:39,586 --> 00:06:42,569
Because the parent should be guiding the child, right?

74
00:06:42,922 --> 00:06:44,704
But the anger is not necessary.

75
00:06:44,723 --> 00:06:45,764
That's the point.

76
00:06:46,305 --> 00:06:49,567
Insistence, you know, you will do this, this is what you're going to do.

77
00:06:49,949 --> 00:06:50,588
That's necessary.

78
00:06:50,608 --> 00:06:52,471
The child has to be trained.

79
00:06:54,452 --> 00:06:55,454
But the anger is not necessary.

80
00:06:55,473 --> 00:06:57,915
The anger is coming from somewhere else.

81
00:07:01,019 --> 00:07:01,759
Frustration.

82
00:07:01,779 --> 00:07:04,442
See, all that is not necessary.

83
00:07:04,461 --> 00:07:08,165
It happens because the attachment is there.

84
00:07:08,446 --> 00:07:10,767
If, you know, if...

85
00:07:11,930 --> 00:07:18,000
little Johnny from down the road gets a black eye, well, you're very happy, you see, because he, I mean, deserves it.

86
00:07:18,019 --> 00:07:21,966
But if your Johnny gets a black eye, well, all hell's let loose, you know.

87
00:07:22,146 --> 00:07:25,451
You're up there knocking on people's doors.

88
00:07:25,471 --> 00:07:27,956
Today's your attachment, see.

89
00:07:27,976 --> 00:07:36,850
If a child falls over and hurts itself, and the parent knows that the child has not actually hurt themselves, just a scratch or something, then they're very comforting, see.

90
00:07:36,891 --> 00:07:37,853
No problem, you see.

91
00:07:38,692 --> 00:07:43,978
But if they think the child's actually really hurt themselves, broken a limb, banged their heads badly, it's panic.

92
00:07:45,641 --> 00:07:50,906
Now, you take the child to the hospital, supposing the staff began to panic.

93
00:07:52,728 --> 00:07:53,949
Ridiculous, isn't it?

94
00:07:53,970 --> 00:08:00,538
You take the child with a broken arm, and the nurses are panicking, the doctor's panicking, you think, oh, bloody hell, what's happening?

95
00:08:00,577 --> 00:08:06,404
So you don't expect professionals to panic, but you expect the mother and father to panic.

96
00:08:07,024 --> 00:08:08,447
So the panic is...

97
00:08:09,202 --> 00:08:10,185
is unnecessary.

98
00:08:10,384 --> 00:08:13,329
That's coming from that wrong relationship, you see.

99
00:08:16,074 --> 00:08:16,754
You mean the death?

100
00:08:17,355 --> 00:08:17,735
Ah, yes.

101
00:08:18,057 --> 00:08:22,744
Well, that, of course, is a real horror story for a parent.

102
00:08:23,345 --> 00:08:29,634
But the grief, you see, the loss of somebody, the grief we feel is not a measure of love.

103
00:08:29,954 --> 00:08:31,016
It's the measure of attachment.

104
00:08:32,178 --> 00:08:32,379
See?

105
00:08:33,980 --> 00:08:37,606
And if you don't see that, then you get yourself into a double bind.

106
00:08:37,924 --> 00:08:42,328
Because every time you grief lessons, you say to yourself, I don't love them anymore.

107
00:08:43,149 --> 00:08:47,273
So to re-establish your love with a person, you've got to re-establish your grief.

108
00:08:48,333 --> 00:08:50,115
There's no way out of that, you see.

109
00:08:51,216 --> 00:09:01,806
So the grief is the, you know, it's like something has been ripped out of your heart and it's left you with a rawness, right?

110
00:09:01,826 --> 00:09:06,750
And this person has been part of your interior life, you see.

111
00:09:07,456 --> 00:09:12,341
It's been part of your happiness, been part of your grief, but it's been part of your life.

112
00:09:12,380 --> 00:09:15,865
And suddenly they're ripped out, you see, and you've just got this gaping wound.

113
00:09:16,485 --> 00:09:22,351
And you've got this ghost inside you who keeps reappearing, but you can't, it doesn't grow, it doesn't move anymore.

114
00:09:22,371 --> 00:09:25,394
It doesn't, it doesn't, like nothing happens to it.

115
00:09:25,414 --> 00:09:25,836
See what I mean?

116
00:09:26,096 --> 00:09:27,898
So there's your grief.

117
00:09:27,957 --> 00:09:35,285
Now, normally speaking, in a grief process, this is what they say, you know, it takes nine months, the first three being quite terrible.

118
00:09:36,092 --> 00:09:39,576
And if it goes on after nine months, then there's something chronic about it.

119
00:09:39,596 --> 00:09:44,061
There's something wrong in the way the person is relating to that death.

120
00:09:45,182 --> 00:09:52,889
So I had an elderly woman came, and she'd been grieving the loss of her son for five years, for heaven's sake.

121
00:09:54,091 --> 00:10:01,357
So when I pointed this out to her, and I said, actually, what real love is, is allowing a person to go.

122
00:10:01,912 --> 00:10:04,475
Now, if that person lives with his time, you let them go, you see.

123
00:10:04,856 --> 00:10:08,783
Just like I mentioned this morning about the mother with the child who leaves home.

124
00:10:09,164 --> 00:10:10,386
She's ready to let go.

125
00:10:10,407 --> 00:10:11,548
That was their time, you see.

126
00:10:11,568 --> 00:10:15,576
And then, when you do that, of course, you begin to rejoice in the relationship you had.

127
00:10:15,936 --> 00:10:18,520
It comes up with joy, you see.

128
00:10:18,541 --> 00:10:22,326
Well, she was back the next week saying all her grief had gone.

129
00:10:22,346 --> 00:10:25,572
She was amazed, because she just got locked into that double bind, you see.

130
00:10:31,341 --> 00:10:37,028
But you wouldn't feel that great if you... Ah, well, you'd have to be fully liberated to do that.

131
00:10:37,368 --> 00:10:38,688
You'd have to be fully liberated.

132
00:10:38,708 --> 00:10:45,336
You see, when the Buddha died, when the Buddha passed, we don't say, we usually say, pass into parinibbā, total nibbā.

133
00:10:46,456 --> 00:10:48,259
The young monks who were around began to cry.

134
00:10:49,340 --> 00:10:52,864
And all the elders who were fully liberated said, what are you crying for?

135
00:10:53,644 --> 00:10:55,206
You knew he was going to rise and pass away.

136
00:10:55,927 --> 00:10:57,528
Which sounds very glib, you know.

137
00:10:58,568 --> 00:11:01,331
But that was their relationship to him as their teacher.

138
00:11:02,375 --> 00:11:05,198
You keep saying that people are liberated.

139
00:11:05,219 --> 00:11:05,860
Is that the aim?

140
00:11:06,159 --> 00:11:07,182
Is that the intention?

141
00:11:07,581 --> 00:11:09,945
It's to be liberated from suffering.

142
00:11:09,965 --> 00:11:10,446
That's the aim.

143
00:11:11,067 --> 00:11:12,889
Now, you have to be careful what we mean by that.

144
00:11:12,908 --> 00:11:14,270
We're not talking about physical pain.

145
00:11:14,331 --> 00:11:15,793
So long as there's a body, there's pain.

146
00:11:16,494 --> 00:11:23,303
But the suffering is, you know, depression, anxiety, frustration, the whole gamut of human misery.

147
00:11:23,323 --> 00:11:25,386
Addiction, compulsive behavior, all that.

148
00:11:25,687 --> 00:11:26,408
You see, all that.

149
00:11:26,876 --> 00:11:35,246
we're completely liberated from because our relationship to the world completely changes we're not seeking happiness there anymore why?

150
00:11:35,586 --> 00:11:54,370
because we've found this inner happiness which is not dependent on the world that's the meaning of Nibbana now every time you're in that position of the observer you're very close to it but we always define happiness by an emotional state see

151
00:11:55,631 --> 00:11:58,914
So when you say to yourself, when you say I'm happy, what do you actually mean?

152
00:11:59,235 --> 00:12:03,038
If you say to somebody I'm happy, what is it you actually are referring to?

153
00:12:03,080 --> 00:12:04,140
See?

154
00:12:05,721 --> 00:12:06,682
It's your emotions, isn't it?

155
00:12:07,464 --> 00:12:09,004
It's a feeling of happiness in you.

156
00:12:09,446 --> 00:12:10,407
Well, that's unreliable.

157
00:12:11,807 --> 00:12:24,441
So if you stop saying I'm happy when you are feeling happy, then it's just, I mentioned Blake's little phrase, to kiss a joy as it flies is to live in eternity's sunrise.

158
00:12:25,432 --> 00:12:25,633
See?

159
00:12:26,153 --> 00:12:33,524
And every time something good comes up many times, the best thing is to feel gratitude, to thank it.

160
00:12:33,543 --> 00:12:34,105
See?

161
00:12:34,125 --> 00:12:34,725
And then let go.

162
00:12:34,846 --> 00:12:35,265
That's it.

163
00:12:35,285 --> 00:12:35,706
Finished.

164
00:12:36,106 --> 00:12:37,229
That will never come again.

165
00:12:37,269 --> 00:12:40,712
Something similar may arise, but that will never come again.

166
00:12:40,732 --> 00:12:44,197
That's the nature of impermanence.

167
00:12:44,217 --> 00:12:46,981
Nothing ever repeats itself.

168
00:12:47,001 --> 00:12:48,703
See?

169
00:12:48,764 --> 00:12:54,731
So if we get into the habit of saying, thank you very much, goodbye,

170
00:12:55,538 --> 00:12:56,779
Finish, you see?

171
00:12:56,980 --> 00:12:57,640
Then the next thing.

172
00:13:01,326 --> 00:13:01,986
Yes?

173
00:13:02,006 --> 00:13:15,465
Do you know if you're, like, does that, does it mean kind of, like, do you know the way you said people who weren't in one issue did that, but, like, become liberated, but how, like, do you, if you're not?

174
00:13:15,485 --> 00:13:20,091
Like, how do you actually be in the world and... Ah, well.

175
00:13:20,631 --> 00:13:22,575
No, well, that, yes, that's a good way of putting it.

176
00:13:22,927 --> 00:13:24,788
In fact, that's Jesus, isn't it?

177
00:13:24,849 --> 00:13:26,431
To be in the world, but not of it.

178
00:13:26,451 --> 00:13:26,971
See?

179
00:13:26,991 --> 00:13:27,712
I mean, that's perfect.

180
00:13:27,732 --> 00:13:30,176
You couldn't say it more simply, more direct than that.

181
00:13:30,196 --> 00:13:32,339
To be in the world, but not of it.

182
00:13:32,359 --> 00:13:43,293
So, we've done the practice of meditation, which is about understanding, about clarifying the way we understand things, and about purifying the heart.

183
00:13:43,312 --> 00:13:47,778
Then we did the metta, which is about establishing a right relationship, right?

184
00:13:48,339 --> 00:13:50,621
So now, you have to take that

185
00:13:50,821 --> 00:13:55,167
wisdom and goodwill into your daily life.

186
00:13:55,187 --> 00:14:03,278
And every time you walk into a situation, you have to stop and think, well, what is the right attitude for this situation?

187
00:14:04,080 --> 00:14:07,403
And just in that way, you move towards liberation.

188
00:14:09,626 --> 00:14:11,109
So that's the Eightfold Path.

189
00:14:11,230 --> 00:14:20,743
Right understanding, right attitude, right speech, right action, right livelihood, where we talked about a basic attitude of service

190
00:14:21,735 --> 00:14:22,136
That's it.

191
00:14:23,337 --> 00:14:35,674
And these things are sort of feedback loops because if you, for instance, have an understanding, just an intellectual understanding of interconnectedness, right?

192
00:14:35,695 --> 00:14:40,101
You've thought about it and you've seen how everything is dependent on something else.

193
00:14:40,241 --> 00:14:41,724
Everything is contingent.

194
00:14:41,823 --> 00:14:43,826
Everything arises because of something.

195
00:14:43,846 --> 00:14:46,009
Everything is interdependent, right?

196
00:14:46,029 --> 00:14:48,592
Now, if it stays at that level, it's absolutely sterile.

197
00:14:49,654 --> 00:14:49,735
See?

198
00:14:50,203 --> 00:14:54,028
But when you actually bring it down into an attitude, you're moving towards love.

199
00:14:54,229 --> 00:14:57,893
Because love is the acceptance of interdependence at the heart level.

200
00:14:58,673 --> 00:15:00,216
And compassion and joy.

201
00:15:00,735 --> 00:15:05,642
If it stays at the heart level, you might feel good about it, but it doesn't do you any good.

202
00:15:05,841 --> 00:15:07,063
It's got to move into action.

203
00:15:08,325 --> 00:15:14,371
And as you act from those attitudes, it feeds back into the understanding.

204
00:15:14,392 --> 00:15:18,236
Because you're actually experiencing interconnectedness.

205
00:15:20,966 --> 00:15:40,153
in that way you spin yourself to Nibbana without getting dizzy so 25 years do you say about it?

206
00:15:40,173 --> 00:15:49,826
oh at least oh at least well in Buddhism 25 is a lifetime but you know we don't want to get too depressed we want to start

207
00:15:50,818 --> 00:15:53,562
You start where you are and you just keep moving forward.

208
00:15:53,643 --> 00:15:58,849
And the thing is not to get upset when we fall over.

209
00:15:59,590 --> 00:16:04,876
I mean, you know, I always point to, what's his name?

210
00:16:06,198 --> 00:16:07,900
Yeah, Ginger Rogers and Fred Astaire.

211
00:16:08,601 --> 00:16:09,943
I can't remember the film it was in.

212
00:16:10,083 --> 00:16:13,048
But you remember, she's trying to teach him how to dance.

213
00:16:14,048 --> 00:16:15,490
And he pretends to fall over, you know.

214
00:16:16,412 --> 00:16:18,615
And they have that song, you know, pick yourself up.

215
00:16:19,033 --> 00:16:22,359
dust yourself off, start all over again.

216
00:16:22,379 --> 00:16:22,700
That's it.

217
00:16:23,541 --> 00:16:23,721
See?

218
00:16:23,821 --> 00:16:29,951
Every time you fall, you just pick yourself up.

219
00:16:29,971 --> 00:16:30,051
See?

220
00:16:30,071 --> 00:16:30,951
So we're bound to fail.

221
00:16:31,312 --> 00:16:31,833
See, that's the point.

222
00:16:31,854 --> 00:16:32,554
We're bound to fail.

223
00:16:34,638 --> 00:16:35,620
But we keep trying, you see.

224
00:16:35,639 --> 00:16:37,001
Keep trying.

225
00:16:37,022 --> 00:16:38,804
And the failures get less intense.

226
00:16:40,908 --> 00:16:46,135
Yeah.

227
00:16:46,155 --> 00:16:46,876
Are we not, like, all heading there?

228
00:16:46,897 --> 00:16:47,437
